29:56.828 --> 29:58.329
- Watch this.

29:58.363 --> 30:00.632
♪ ♪

30:00.665 --> 30:02.734
[whoosh]

30:02.767 --> 30:03.935
[audience exclaiming]

30:03.968 --> 30:06.037
- You don't believe it?

30:06.070 --> 30:07.572
Watch it again.

30:07.605 --> 30:10.275
♪ ♪

30:10.308 --> 30:11.843
Yeah.

30:15.013 --> 30:16.614
[whoosh]

30:16.648 --> 30:17.749
See?

30:17.782 --> 30:18.750
[cheers and applause]

30:18.783 --> 30:19.818
Now you try.

30:19.851 --> 30:21.085
Choose a color.

30:21.119 --> 30:22.320
- Sure.
I'll try green.

30:22.353 --> 30:24.689
- Green.
Okay.

30:26.291 --> 30:27.926
You try.

30:27.959 --> 30:30.328
Please.

30:30.361 --> 30:31.362
[whoosh]

30:31.396 --> 30:33.198
And look at what you've done.

30:33.231 --> 30:34.566
- Hey!

30:34.599 --> 30:35.600
[cheers and applause]

30:35.633 --> 30:36.601
- Oh. Very good.

30:36.634 --> 30:38.436
Very good.

30:38.469 --> 30:41.206
But I wonder if it's
the cube that is magical,

30:41.239 --> 30:43.575
or the bag.

30:43.608 --> 30:45.276
Alyson?
- Mm-hmm.

30:45.310 --> 30:47.912
- Which color is your favorite?

30:47.946 --> 30:49.514
- Well, I just picked
my favorite.

30:49.547 --> 30:51.482
But I'll change to blue.

30:51.516 --> 30:52.951
- Oh.
Change to blue.

30:52.984 --> 30:54.586
Okay.
- Yeah.

30:57.222 --> 31:02.694
- So wouldn't it be amazing
if this bag

31:02.727 --> 31:07.365
could magically change
the color of your cube

31:07.398 --> 31:09.968
without me touching it?

31:10.001 --> 31:11.236
- Yeah.

31:11.269 --> 31:14.205
- So please take the bag

31:14.239 --> 31:17.075
and shake it.

31:18.009 --> 31:19.177
Yeah.
Enough.

31:19.210 --> 31:21.512
[laughter]

31:21.546 --> 31:24.816
Wow.
Amazing.

31:24.849 --> 31:27.619
All six sides changed.

31:27.652 --> 31:29.888
[cheers and applause]

31:29.921 --> 31:31.489
But I don't think

31:31.522 --> 31:33.491
it's the cube that is magical.

31:33.524 --> 31:34.559
Or the bag.

31:34.592 --> 31:36.828
It's something else.

31:36.861 --> 31:39.597
So let me prove it to you

31:39.631 --> 31:41.566
with another cube.

31:41.599 --> 31:48.640
♪ ♪

31:50.108 --> 31:51.509
How about this one?

31:51.542 --> 31:52.777
[dramatic music]

31:52.810 --> 31:56.214
Or this one?

31:57.282 --> 31:59.784
I also have another one.

32:01.085 --> 32:04.422
And one more.

32:04.455 --> 32:07.492
Oh.
This one is my favorite.

32:07.525 --> 32:08.660
- [laughs]

32:08.693 --> 32:11.729
- Oh, this one is so cute.

32:11.763 --> 32:14.332
This one is very popular.

32:14.365 --> 32:15.600
Oh.

32:15.633 --> 32:18.202
I recommend this.
No reason.

32:18.236 --> 32:19.337
[laughter]

32:19.370 --> 32:23.107
And--oh.
This one is pretty good.

32:23.141 --> 32:26.377
And this one--

32:26.411 --> 32:29.580
also, this one is very famous.

32:29.614 --> 32:31.382
- [laughing]
Oh.

32:31.416 --> 32:33.017
Wow.

32:33.051 --> 32:34.619
- This is very...

32:34.652 --> 32:35.720
[cheers and applause]

32:35.753 --> 32:37.322
Puzzling.

32:37.355 --> 32:39.424
The truth is

32:39.457 --> 32:42.794
the cubes are not magic.

32:42.827 --> 32:45.463
The bags are not magic.

32:45.496 --> 32:47.332
You are magic.

32:47.365 --> 32:48.733
- Hey!

32:48.766 --> 32:50.401
[cheers and applause]

32:50.435 --> 32:52.570
- Please hold out your hand.

33:04.916 --> 33:06.417
What is your favorite color?

33:06.451 --> 33:07.986
- Blue.

33:08.019 --> 33:09.854
- You chose the color, right?

33:09.887 --> 33:10.888
- Yes.

33:10.922 --> 33:13.791
- And give me your magic.

33:13.825 --> 33:15.259
Like this.

33:16.361 --> 33:17.729
Thank you.

33:17.762 --> 33:18.997
Check it out.

33:19.030 --> 33:20.164
- [gasps]
all: Ooh.

33:20.198 --> 33:21.366
- Thank you, Alyson.

33:21.399 --> 33:22.533
- Wow.

33:22.567 --> 33:23.668
[cheers and applause]

33:23.701 --> 33:25.737
Whoa.
- Thank you very much.

33:25.770 --> 33:27.405
Thank you.
- Wow.

33:27.438 --> 33:29.874
Takamiz Usui!

33:29.907 --> 33:31.042
[cheers and applause]

33:31.075 --> 33:33.511
Ahh.

33:33.544 --> 33:35.179
Wow.

33:35.213 --> 33:38.616
So why did you choose
to do magic with the cube?

33:38.649 --> 33:41.486
- [speaking Japanese]

33:50.161 --> 33:52.530
- So you're the pioneer
of this style?

34:03.841 --> 34:06.144
- It's his secret,
and that's his trick.

34:06.177 --> 34:07.578
- Yes.
- Yes.

34:07.612 --> 34:08.880
All right.

34:08.913 --> 34:10.715
Well, let's see how much
your unique techniques...

34:10.748 --> 34:12.583
- Mm-hmm.
- Puzzled the boys.

34:12.617 --> 34:13.918
Boys.

34:13.951 --> 34:15.920
- Hello, Takamiz.
- Hi.

34:15.953 --> 34:17.121
- I've gotta ask you.

34:17.155 --> 34:20.024
This is the most important
question to me.

34:20.058 --> 34:22.393
Did you invent
this stuff yourself?

34:22.427 --> 34:25.463
- [speaking Japanese]

34:26.864 --> 34:30.001
- Everything that you saw
tonight, I invented it.

34:30.034 --> 34:31.235
- Whoa.

34:31.269 --> 34:34.305
[cheers and applause]

34:35.540 --> 34:38.443
Unbelievable.
Unbelievable.

34:38.476 --> 34:41.746
There are feats of engineering

34:41.779 --> 34:45.049
that we--we know are there

34:45.083 --> 34:46.184
and just beautiful.

34:46.217 --> 34:49.420
Also, it's not just

34:49.454 --> 34:51.556
props and inventions.

34:51.589 --> 34:54.759
There's also just raw skill

34:54.792 --> 34:57.295
that's being done
at blinding speed

34:57.328 --> 34:59.664
that just--just amazed us.

34:59.697 --> 35:03.234
We--we--we loved the routine.

35:03.267 --> 35:07.371
But I do not think,
uh, you fooled us.

35:08.840 --> 35:10.641
And I tried to sneak
some stuff in there.

35:10.675 --> 35:12.643
I don't know
whether the translation

35:12.677 --> 35:13.778
is gonna get through.

35:13.811 --> 35:16.013
- So do you think
you fooled them?

35:16.047 --> 35:18.049
- [speaking Japanese]

35:18.082 --> 35:19.650
[both laughing]

35:19.684 --> 35:21.452
- I thought I did.
- Mm.

35:21.486 --> 35:22.987
- You thought you did?

35:23.020 --> 35:25.756
Do you need
a little more information?

35:25.790 --> 35:30.328
- We can't seem
to decide on this.

35:30.361 --> 35:33.598
I will repeat
for people watching

35:33.631 --> 35:35.233
that we have microphones on,

35:35.266 --> 35:37.902
and the judges hear
everything that I say,

35:37.935 --> 35:39.237
everything that Teller says.

35:39.270 --> 35:41.139
And the judges also know

35:41.172 --> 35:43.040
how every detail
of the tricks are done.

35:43.074 --> 35:44.542
So up in the booth,

35:44.575 --> 35:46.043
they're listening
to everything,

35:46.077 --> 35:49.113
deciding whether
what we said

35:49.147 --> 35:52.550
is close enough
to what Takamiz actually did.

35:52.583 --> 35:54.118
It is now out of our hands,

35:54.152 --> 35:56.354
and it's in the hands
of the adults.

35:56.387 --> 35:58.389
- So we're going to the judges.

35:58.422 --> 36:00.324
And the judges are telling me

36:00.358 --> 36:03.728
that Penn and Teller
do know how you did the trick.

36:03.761 --> 36:05.463
You did not fool them.
- Okay.

36:05.496 --> 36:07.098
- But thank you so much.

36:07.131 --> 36:08.499
- Okay.
Thank you.

36:08.533 --> 36:09.901
Thank you.

36:09.934 --> 36:13.037
- Takamiz Usui!

36:13.070 --> 36:15.640
Penn and Teller
aren't done with you yet.

36:15.673 --> 36:18.743
You get to see them perform
one of their newest routines

36:18.776 --> 36:21.112
for the very first time
on television

36:21.145 --> 36:22.914
when "Fool Us" returns.

36:22.947 --> 36:25.917
[cheers and applause]

36:25.950 --> 36:27.451
♪ ♪

36:30.488 --> 36:32.957
♪ ♪

36:32.990 --> 36:34.225
[cheers and applause]

36:34.258 --> 36:37.195
- We close out every show
in the best possible way,

36:37.228 --> 36:40.231
with a performance
by one of the greatest duos

36:40.264 --> 36:42.500
in the history
of entertainment.

36:42.533 --> 36:44.001
Ladies and gentlemen,

36:44.035 --> 36:47.371
the incomparable
Penn and Teller!

36:47.405 --> 36:49.073
[cheers and applause]

36:49.106 --> 36:50.441
- Thank you.
Thank you.

36:50.474 --> 36:53.678
Um, we're gonna do--

36:53.711 --> 36:55.646
we're gonna do
some illegal stuff for you.

36:55.680 --> 36:57.048
We're gonna get
a little bit illegal.

36:57.081 --> 37:00.017
And we need to borrow
a bank note from someone.

37:00.017 --> 37:01.285
A bill.

37:01.319 --> 37:03.988
Now, a lot of magicians
try to borrow a hundred,

37:04.021 --> 37:05.456
or a 50 or a 20

37:05.489 --> 37:07.325
to make their tricks
seem more important.

37:07.358 --> 37:08.826
But all we need is a single.

37:08.859 --> 37:10.361
A one single dollar bill.

37:10.394 --> 37:11.662
We're not even
gonna take it from you.

37:11.696 --> 37:13.431
I'm gonna buy it from you.

37:13.464 --> 37:15.266
You have noth--
nothing to risk at all.

37:15.299 --> 37:17.268
I'll buy a dollar bill
from somebody.

37:17.301 --> 37:18.569
Anybody have a dollar bill
in the audience?

37:18.603 --> 37:19.904
Okay.
Somebody there?

37:19.937 --> 37:21.672
And you have a dollar bill?
You're right close.

37:21.706 --> 37:23.374
Come on up here.

37:23.407 --> 37:25.142
And bring
your dollar bill up here.

37:25.176 --> 37:26.344
[cheers and applause]

37:26.377 --> 37:28.246
And what is your name,
our newest friend?

37:28.279 --> 37:29.814
- Christian.
- Hello, Christian.

37:29.847 --> 37:31.048
My name is Penn.
Nice to meet you.

37:31.082 --> 37:32.350
Can I see your--your bill here?

37:32.383 --> 37:33.884
Just stand over here
next to me.

37:33.918 --> 37:35.720
And I'm gonna take your bill,

37:35.753 --> 37:36.754
and I'm gonna give you my bill,

37:36.787 --> 37:37.855
and kiss it good-bye.

37:37.888 --> 37:39.190
Mwah.

37:39.223 --> 37:41.259
And I'm gonna kind of
roll this up on the inside

37:41.292 --> 37:42.793
so that that's
where my spit is.

37:42.827 --> 37:44.428
And keep that away
from your nose and mouth.

37:44.462 --> 37:47.064
You don't know what kind
of vector I am, okay?

37:47.098 --> 37:50.301
Now, Christian,
I'm gonna have you--

37:50.334 --> 37:51.602
know this serial number.

37:51.636 --> 37:53.304
Serial number's really
important in this trick.

37:53.337 --> 37:54.705
So I'm just gonna rip the bill.

37:54.739 --> 37:57.675
Now, this is still legal--
[sighs]

37:57.708 --> 37:59.143
it's still--I'm trying
to be very careful

37:59.176 --> 38:00.211
that I don't rip
too much of it.

38:00.244 --> 38:01.779
'Cause it's still legal tender

38:01.812 --> 38:03.147
if you have more than half.

38:03.180 --> 38:05.116
So I'm gonna have
more than half here.

38:05.149 --> 38:06.284
It's really fun
to rip a dollar bill

38:06.317 --> 38:07.585
if you wanna rip a little bit.

38:07.618 --> 38:08.886
You wanna get the final bit?
Just rip it off there.

38:08.919 --> 38:10.187
There you go.
There you go.

38:10.221 --> 38:11.989
Now just--you've got
the serial number there.

38:12.023 --> 38:13.991
And now I bought
this bill from you.

38:14.025 --> 38:16.093
This was your bill.
Now it's mine.

38:16.127 --> 38:17.728
And Christian,
I'm gonna do something illegal.

38:17.762 --> 38:20.865
It always perplexed me
why this was illegal

38:20.898 --> 38:23.934
'cause destroying money
just means that

38:23.968 --> 38:26.370
everybody else's money is worth
just a little bit more.

38:26.404 --> 38:27.505
But it is illegal.

38:27.538 --> 38:29.106
Now, I wanna tell you,
Christian,

38:29.140 --> 38:30.841
this theater we're in now,

38:30.875 --> 38:33.210
Penn & Teller,
has my name in it.

38:33.244 --> 38:35.112
The show,
"Penn & Teller: Fool Us,"

38:35.146 --> 38:36.347
my name in it.

38:36.380 --> 38:39.183
Side of the building,
300 feet tall,

38:39.216 --> 38:40.351
my picture.

38:40.384 --> 38:42.019
I'm doing very well, Christian.

38:42.053 --> 38:43.120
[laughter]
Very well.

38:43.154 --> 38:46.223
Which means money
means nothing to me.

38:46.257 --> 38:47.725
I'm gonna destroy it.
Look at this.

38:47.758 --> 38:50.127
I'm just destroying money
right in front of you.

38:50.161 --> 38:53.331
To me, it's just
green confetti.

38:53.364 --> 38:54.665
[laughter]
I don't care.

38:54.699 --> 38:56.701
The bill that was yours
that I bought from you,

38:56.734 --> 38:58.302
I have now destroyed.

38:58.336 --> 39:00.471
Expect for that serial number
you have there.

39:00.504 --> 39:02.573
But you know, Teller and I
have been working together

39:02.606 --> 39:04.742
45 years.

39:04.775 --> 39:06.777
And there's
a little bit of rivalry.

39:06.811 --> 39:10.381
When I do something,
Teller wants to do it more.

39:10.414 --> 39:13.451
So Teller's gonna do something
way more illegal.

39:13.484 --> 39:15.119
'Cause he has
something in there

39:15.152 --> 39:17.488
that it's illegal to possess,

39:17.521 --> 39:20.491
and that is treasury paper.

39:20.524 --> 39:23.694
This is the paper
that bills are printed on.

39:23.728 --> 39:26.630
It's made by the Crane Paper
Company in Massachusetts,

39:26.664 --> 39:27.932
and they've been making it

39:27.965 --> 39:30.501
since before there
was a United States.

39:30.534 --> 39:32.870
'Cause they made it
during the Revolutionary War.

39:32.903 --> 39:33.938
Now, if you examine that,
you'll see

39:33.971 --> 39:35.740
it does not feel
like regular paper.

39:35.773 --> 39:37.341
It feels like a bill

39:37.375 --> 39:40.244
because it is 75% cotton,
25% linen.

39:40.277 --> 39:41.679
It's called rag paper.

39:41.712 --> 39:42.947
Now, I don't know
how good your eyes are,

39:42.980 --> 39:44.014
but hold it up to the light.

39:44.048 --> 39:45.282
I can't see this.
Maybe you can.

39:45.316 --> 39:48.586
You'll be able to see
little tiny, tiny threads

39:48.619 --> 39:51.922
of red, blue, and metallic.

39:51.956 --> 39:53.057
You see that there?

39:53.090 --> 39:54.258
That makes it harder
to counterfeit.

39:54.291 --> 39:57.261
Now, possessing that
is illegal.

39:57.294 --> 39:59.263
But Teller's gonna go
a step further.

39:59.296 --> 40:02.466
I destroyed a dollar bill
in a felony.

40:02.500 --> 40:03.634
But Teller's gonna risk

40:03.667 --> 40:06.570
a $250,000 fine

40:06.604 --> 40:08.406
and 20 years in prison

40:08.439 --> 40:10.641
to do something really stupid.

40:10.674 --> 40:12.143
He is counterfeiting

40:12.176 --> 40:15.112
a $1 bill, Christian.

40:15.146 --> 40:16.914
[laughter]
A $1 bill.

40:16.947 --> 40:19.483
And not even
the complete $1 bill.

40:19.517 --> 40:21.585
There's one part
he didn't bother with.

40:21.619 --> 40:24.922
That part right there that's
kind of vaguely shaped.

40:24.955 --> 40:27.091
Like what you have there,
Christian.

40:27.124 --> 40:29.794
You have your serial number
right there.

40:29.827 --> 40:32.630
Now, we've gonna check this.
There's a serial number.

40:32.663 --> 40:34.999
We're gonna see if it matches
the serial number on this bill.

40:35.032 --> 40:38.269
So very loudly, Christian, read
out the serial number, please.

40:38.302 --> 40:44.108
- L-0-9-1-7-2-3-2-8-R.

40:44.141 --> 40:45.810
- Yes!
Perfect!

40:45.843 --> 40:47.278
[cheers and applause]

40:47.311 --> 40:49.847
Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh,
oh, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh.

40:49.880 --> 40:51.282
After all these years,

40:51.315 --> 40:53.017
all these years
of Penn and Teller,

40:53.050 --> 40:54.385
you think we bluff?

40:54.985 --> 40:56.487
You think we bluff?

40:56.520 --> 40:57.955
There's the serial number
right there.

40:57.988 --> 40:59.023
Now, there's your piece.

40:59.056 --> 41:00.458
Now, yours looks like

41:00.491 --> 41:02.593
you've been carrying it around
in the bottom of your shoe.

41:02.626 --> 41:04.028
